We also created a separate index definition on the collection
containing all 15.3M items, which includes filters on two fields
to enable pre-filtered queries against this dataset.```javascript
db.large_amazon_dataset.createSearchIndex(
  "vectorSearch",
  "large_vector_index",
  {
    "fields": [
      {
        "numDimensions": 2048,
        "path": "embedding",
        "quantization": "scalar", // adjust to binary when needed
        "similarity": "dotProduct",
        "type": "vector"
      },
      {
        "path": "category",
        "type": "filter"
      },
      {
        "path": "price",
        "type": "filter"
      }
    ]
  }
)
```We ran vector search queries, both unfiltered and filtered, against the large indexed dataset:**Unfiltered-query:**Unfiltered Query```python
# unfiltered query
query = [
  {
    "$vectorSearch": {
      "index": "large_vector_index",
      "path": "embedding",
      "queryVector": embedding.tolist(),
      "limit": k,
      "numCandidates": candidates,
    }
  },
  {
    "$project": {"embedding": 0}
  }
]
```**Filtered-query:**Filtered Query```python
# filtered query
query = [
  {
    "$vectorSearch": {
      "index": "large_vector_index",
      "path": "embedding",
      "queryVector": embedding.tolist(),
      "limit": k,
      "numCandidates": candidates,
      "filter": {"$and": [{'price': {'$lte': 1000}}, {'category': {'$eq': "Pet Supplies"}}]}
    }
  },
  {
    "$project": {"embedding": 0}
  }
]
```> **Note:** Both query patterns exclude the embedding fields in the output by using
> [$project](manual/reference/operator/aggregation/project) stage. This is always recommended to reduce
> latency unless you need embeddings in your results.

